This grant supported the establishment of the Applied Biodiversity Science Doctoral Program (ABS) at Texas A&amp;M University.  Research and graduate training is focused on two cross-cutting themes: A) Ecological Functions and Biodiversity; and B) Communities and Governance. Through this program faculty mentors from 11 departments with training and expertise in allied disciplines including conservation biology, ecological economics, cultural anthropology, human ecology, human geography, evolution, and ecology, are brought together with students, in collaboration with international partners, to develop dissertations related to the two research themes.  Graduates of the ABS program are prepared to face the multidimensional challenges of global biodiversity loss and emerge qualified to assume directorships and academic appointments to help mitigate this loss.

Outcomes resulting from this grant include:

Direct support to 24 PhD students, each receiving two years of NSF stipend and additional support for training and research. An additional three international students were funded at identical levels by Texas A&amp;M University support. At least 15 other graduate students are affiliated with the ABS Program and by 2018 the ABS Program will have produced 40 PhDs. The ABS Program has supported a diverse group of students, including women (59%) and members of traditionally underrepresented minorities (45%);
Placement of ABS-trained scientists in academia, government, and NGOs;
A sustained program in Applied Biodiversity Science at TAMU which continues to involve over 20 faculty members from 8 departments and 4 colleges and has attracted over $400,000 in funding from TAMU;
Enhanced collaboration among academic and NGO scientists and conservation stakeholders in the U.S. and abroad;
Strengthened interdisciplinary collaborations among academic programs, departments, and colleges at TAMU;
Internationalization across departments and colleges at TAMU;
A diverse and broad network of biodiversity scientists and strategists dedicated to cross-disciplinary and cross-national collaboration for biodiversity conservation;
ABS-IGERT students and faculty trained to use their research findings to influence and implement biodiversity conservation.
A total of 453 peer-reviewed publications, seven books, 47 book chapters, and 27 conference publications.




In addition to these specific outcomes, this project has resulted in broader impacts to science and society including:

* Greater involvement of underrepresented groups in Applied Biodiversity Sciences;

* Capacity-building of local counterpart scientists and institutions in host countries;

* More effective communication between biodiversity scientists and conservation practitioners;

* Long-term benefits for biodiversity conservation in the U.S.A. and Latin America.



